Product Sales Analytics¶

INTRODUCTION¶

In response to continued demand for creative tools in an increasingly digital world, our company recently launched a new line of office stationery designed to support brainstorming and enhance productivity. To determine the most effective way to promote this new product line, we implemented and tested three distinct sales strategies: Email, Phone Call, and a combined Email + Call approach.

The objective of this analysis is to evaluate the performance of each sales method in terms of customer engagement, sales conversion, and cost-efficiency. This report outlines the steps taken for data validation and cleaning, presents the findings from exploratory data analysis, introduces a key business metric to track performance, and provides actionable recommendations based on the insights.

By applying data-driven evaluation to our sales approach, this report aims to guide future strategy and help ensure the long-term success and scalability of the new product line.

IMPORTING DATA AND DATA VALIDATION¶

Dimension of the original dataset: 15000 rows, 8 columns.

  • The week column contains integer values from 1-6 no null values. No changes to this column were necessary.

  • The sales_method column contains 5 different unique values (Email, Call, Email + Call, em + call, email) and no null values. The column should only contain 3 unique values corresponding to each type of sales method and 2 others are just variations. The column is changed to only contain the following 3 different value types corresponding to each alternate sales method: Email, Call, Email + Call.

  • The customer_id column contains all unique records for each customer and had no missing values. No changes to this column were required.

  • The nb_sold column contains numerical data of the quantity of new products sold. Upon inspection using a boxplot, no extreme outlier is found, so no change is necessary.

  • The revenue column had 1074 null values. It consitutes 7.16% of the total observations which exceeds the 5% threshold. So, the best approach is to carry out an imputation of the mean value of the revenue column by subgroups (sales_method).

  • The years_as_customer column has 0 missing values, however we had 2 rows with invalid values. Since our company was founded in 1984, the maximum amount of years we could have any given customer is 39. Two rows had values with 47 and 63, which is impossible. I assume this was just a mistake in data entry, and the 2 observations are discarded as it consitutes a minute portion of the whole dataset.

  • The nb_site_visits column has 0 missing values and all data is valid. No changes needed to be made to this column

  • The state The column has 0 missing values and 50 unique values corresponding to each state. No changes need to be made to this column

Finally after all the data validation and cleaning I checked for any duplicate rows and found none. After cleaning and validating the data our dataset contains 14998 rows and 8 columns with 0 missing values.

In [7]:
# Imputation of 'revenue' column by subgroup mean
revdict = df.groupby("sales_method")['revenue'].mean().to_dict()
df['revenue'] = df.groupby("sales_method")['revenue'].fillna(df['sales_method'].map(revdict))
print(df.isna().sum())

EXPLORATORY ANALYSIS¶

1) Number of Customers per Sales Method¶

The most popular method of Sales in the 6 weeks period is by Email with 7465 customers, followed by Call with 4961 customers and Email + Call with 2572 customers. As email are much more easier to do, emails can be more scalable in comparison with other methods.

px.bar(cus, x="sales_method", y="customer_id", title = 'Number of Customers per Sales Method', labels={'sales_method': 'Sales Method', 'customer_id': 'Number of Customers'}, color = 'sales_method', color_discrete_map=color).show()

2) Spread of Revenue (Overall and by Method)¶

In [18]:
px.box(df, x="revenue", title="Spread of Revenue (Overall)").show()
In [19]:
px.box(df, x="revenue", y="sales_method", color="sales_method", title="Spread of Revenue (By Method)", color_discrete_map=color).show()

Email (red): Has a relatively high median and wide range. Also shows many outliers above $130. Suggests that email can generate high revenue but with high variability.

Email + Call (green): Shows a tight cluster around the high revenue range ($150–$200), indicating it is consistently effective with high revenue per case and few low values. It also has a lot of outliers above $200.

Call (blue): Has the lowest median and narrowest spread, with revenue mostly between $30–$60. Indicates that calls alone tend to produce lower and more consistent revenue.

Email + Call is the best-performing method, with high and consistent revenue. Performs better than the overall.

Call-only performs the worst in terms of revenue. Performs worst than the overall.

Email-only has a broad distribution, capable of high revenue but with variability.

In [22]:
sales_weekly = df.groupby(['week', 'sales_method'])['nb_sold'].sum().reset_index()

fig5 = px.line(sales_weekly, x='week', y='nb_sold', color='sales_method', color_discrete_map=color,
              title='Sales Volumn Over Time by Sales Method',
              labels={'week': 'Week Since Launch', 'nb_sold': 'Sales Volumn'}).show()

Both Revenue and Sales Volumn Over Time line charts shows similar trends:

  • In week 1, the 'Email' sales method generated the highest revenue ($248K, 24.6K Products), followed by 'Call' ($27K, 5.4K Products) and 'Email + Call' ($20K, 1.3K Products). However, it is important to note that the 'Email' method required the least effort from the sales team, making it the most efficient method during the first week hence more customers are notified through 'Email'.
  • Over the course of the 6 weeks sales generated from the Email sales method consistently decreased. This decline in revenue overtime could indicate diminishing returns from the Email sales method as time goes on.
  • This can be attributed to the decreasing of number of customers being reached by Emails and both Call and Email + Call surpassed Email in terms of customer outreach.
  • The call method shows an overall incresing trend in revenue overtime with some fluctations. Towards the end of the 6 week period the amount of revenue generated from the Call method began to decrease. This follows the trend of number of customer reached closely, which means that Calls should be carried out consistently to maintain the revenue gathered from Calls.
  • The Email + Call method shows a healthy increasing trend of revenue over the 6 week period. Just a small increase in customers reached by Email + Call leads to a quite significant increase in Revenue and Sales Volume.
  • It's possible that this method would be the most beneficial in terms of long-term revenue growth compared to the two other sales methods.

In conclusion, the Email + Call sales method appears to be the most promising in terms of long-term revenue generation, although it does require more effort from the sales team compare to Emails. The Email method starts strong but shows a steady decline, while the Call method has an overall increasing trend but fluctuates more. It is recommended to consider the efficiency and effort required for each method while making a decision on which sales method to continue using.

6) Defining Business Metrics to Track Performance¶

Define the sales effort for each sales method¶

Sales Method Description Effort Score (0-10)
Email 2 emails 1
Call 30 minute call 6
Email + Call 1 email + 10 minute call 3

Average Revenue per Customer Sales Effort (ARCSE) = Total Revenue for Method / Number of customers * Sales effort

In [29]:
# Define the sales effort for each sales method
sales_effort = {
    'Email': 1,
    'Call': 6,
    'Email + Call': 3
}

# Group the data by sales_method and aggregate the total revenue and number of customers
df1 = df.groupby('sales_method').agg({'revenue': 'sum', 'customer_id': 'count'}).reset_index()

# Calculate ARCPSE for each sales method
df1['ARCSE'] = df1.apply(lambda row: row['revenue'] / (row['customer_id'] * sales_effort[row['sales_method']]), axis=1)

# Display the ARCPSE for each sales method
print(df1[['sales_method', 'ARCSE']])

   sales_method      ARCSE
0          Call   7.932815
1         Email  97.128009
2  Email + Call  61.217264

Email has the highest ARCSE (97.13) — it brings in the most revenue per unit of effort. So it is the most cost-effective among the 3 sales methods.

Email + Call has the second highest ARCSE (61.22) — moderate effort with solid returns.

Call alone is the least efficient (7.93), likely due to high time cost.

CONCLUSION AND RECOMMENDATIONS¶

  1. Email + Call is the Most Effective Overall

  • Consistently high revenue with a tight distribution around high values (median ~ $150–$200).

  • Highest customer engagement (avg. 26.77 site visits).

  • Best conversion efficiency (45.67%) — converts visits into sales most effectively.

  • Strong upward trend in revenue and sales over time.

  • ARCSE of 61.22 suggests a solid return on moderate sales effort.

Insight: This method balances effectiveness and effort well. It’s highly engaging and reliable in driving both revenue and product sales.

Recommendation:

  • Scale this method where possible.

  • Automate the email step to reduce total effort per customer.

  • Train sales teams for efficient, high-impact follow-up calls (~10 mins).

  1. Email Alone is the Most Cost-Efficient (ARCSE Leader)

  • Highest ARCSE (97.13) — outstanding revenue per unit of effort.

  • High customer reach and early performance peak in Week 1.

  • Declines in performance over time, likely due to saturation and declining customer responsiveness.

  • Wide revenue range and many outliers — can generate very high returns for some customers.

Insight: Great for broad outreach and low-cost scalability. However, it lacks consistent long-term performance.

Recommendation:

  • Use Email for initial outreach, especially for large or low-priority segments.

  • Consider refreshing content or A/B testing email strategies to sustain engagement over time.

  1. Call Only is the Least Efficient Method

  • Lowest ARCSE (7.93) — low revenue per unit effort due to high time investment (30 mins/customer).

  • Low median revenue, narrow range, and poor engagement metrics.

  • Slight revenue increase in mid-weeks, but drops again toward end.

Insight: High-cost channel with limited return. May be useful only for very high-value accounts.

Recommendation:

  • Limit to high-potential or strategic customers.

  • Explore replacing or complementing calls with video demos, live webinars, or follow-up automation. Or just discard this method.

  1. Geographic Focus — Prioritize Key States

  • California, Texas, New York, and Florida drive the most revenue.

  • These states also represent large customer bases with high conversion potential.

Recommendation:

  • Concentrate sales and marketing efforts in these high-performing states.

  • Use Email + Call to nurture high-value leads in these regions for better ROI.

Summary¶

"Combining email and calls generates the most consistent and high revenue, while calls alone yield the lowest returns. Although email-only has the highest number of interactions, it shows greater variability and less reliability in outcomes."

Business Strategy Recommendations¶

Sales Method Strategy: Expand Email + Call use; automate where possible

Cost Efficiency: Use Email-only for large-scale outreach with minimal human input

Resource Allocation: Restrict Call-only to VIP accounts or special cases

Customer Engagement: Monitor site visits & conversion to optimize message timing & content

Regional Targeting: Prioritize CA, TX, NY, FL for marketing & follow-up investments
